Bring a large #pot{} of @salt{} water to a boil. Wash and dry produce.

Trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; cut into ½-inch-thick half-moons. Zest and quarter @lemon{1}.

Once water is boiling, add @spaghetti{6%ounce} to #pot. Cook, stirring occasionally, until al dente, ~{9-11%minutes}. Reserve 2 cups pasta cooking water, then drain.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{1%tablespoon} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add zucchini and season with 1 tsp @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon}, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. (You'll use more Italian seasoning in the next step.) Cook, stirring occasionally, until softened and lightly browned, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #paper-towel-lined plate{}. Wipe out pan and let cool slightly.

Pat @skin-on salmon{10%ounce} dry with paper towels and season all over with 1 tsp Italian seasoning, @salt{}, and @pepper{}. (Be sure to measure the Italian seasoning—we sent more!)

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add salmon and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes} per side.

Turn off heat; transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest. Once salmon is cool enough to handle, dice into bite-size pieces. Wipe out pan and let cool slightly.

> Swap in chicken or pork for salmon. Cook pork until cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side, or cook salmon (skin sides down) until skin is crisp, 5-7 minutes, then flip and cook until cooked through, 1-2 minutes more.

Return same pan to medium heat. Add 1 1/2 cups reserved pasta cooking water and @cheese roux concentrate{1%ounce}; whisk to combine. Cook, whisking, until slightly thickened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Reduce heat to medium low; whisk in @cream cheese{2%tablespoon} until melted and combined. Season lightly with @pepper{}.

Add drained spaghetti, @Parmesan cheese{3%tablespoon}, 1 tbsp @butter{1%tablespoon}, a big squeeze of lemon juice, and a pinch of lemon zest to pan with sauce. Reduce heat to low. Cook, tossing, until butter is melted and pasta is coated in a creamy sauce, ~{1%minute}.

Add zucchini and diced salmon; toss to coat. Taste and season with salt, pepper, and more lemon juice if desired.

> If needed, stir in more reserved pasta cooking water a splash at a time.

Divide pasta between shallow #bowls{} and serve with any remaining lemon wedges on the side.

> Serve salmon atop pasta.

> Salmon is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.